===========================================================================
MARK RELEVANT IF ANY of these topics are present
===========================================================================
- Legislation, regulations, Acts, or water plans — new, amended, or under
  review (includes statutory instruments, rules, orders, determinations).
- Government announcements, policy decisions, consultations, or
  compliance obligations affecting the water sector.
- Water authority reports, gazette notices, licences, approvals, or
  enforcement actions (including penalties and compliance directions).
- Media releases about water management, supply, quality, conservation,
  infrastructure, trading, or pricing.
- Public safety, environmental, or operational alerts relating to water
  (e.g. algal bloom warnings, dam spills, water restrictions, boil-water
  notices, flood warnings, water contamination events).
- Research, monitoring programs, or data releases about water resources
  (e.g. river flow reports, catchment health data, groundwater studies).
- Community engagement, consultations, or education programs run by
  water authorities, regulators, or government departments.
- Murray-Darling Basin, inter-jurisdictional water agreements, or
  national water policy.

===========================================================================
MARK NOT RELEVANT ONLY IF the article is clearly one of
===========================================================================
- Job listings, tender notices, or procurement announcements with no
  policy or regulatory content.
- Corporate news with no water-management dimension (executive hires,
  office moves, awards, financial earnings unrelated to water policy).
- Content entirely from non-Australian jurisdictions, unless it
  directly affects Australian water law (e.g. bilateral treaties).
- Pure marketing, event promotion, or sponsorship content.
- Duplicate coverage of an event already expected to be in the feed
  (Stage 3 dedup handles exact duplicates; flag here only if the
  duplication is obvious from the text itself).

===========================================================================
TIE-BREAK RULES
===========================================================================
1. DEFAULT TO RELEVANT when uncertain. Editors make the final call —
   a false positive is cheap (editor rejects it in 5 seconds), a false
   negative is expensive (a regulatory item is missed from the newsfeed).
2. If the article spans water AND non-water topics, mark RELEVANT if
   ANY water regulatory angle is present.
3. If the article is international but references Australian agencies,
   Australian law, or an Australian obligation, mark RELEVANT.
4. Short articles (<200 words) with minimal context — if the subject
   matter is water-adjacent, mark RELEVANT and let the editor decide.

===========================================================================
OUTPUT
===========================================================================
Respond with a JSON object and nothing else. No preamble. No markdown
code fences. No commentary. Produce this exact shape:

{"relevant": true, "reason": "<one concise sentence — max 25 words>"}

Rules for the `reason` field:
- One short sentence. No line breaks.
- State the specific topic or rule that triggered the decision
  (e.g. "New water plan made under Water Act 1989 (Vic).").
- If NOT RELEVANT, state which exclusion category applied
  (e.g. "Corporate executive appointment, no regulatory content.").
